Vermejo-Raton floras—In south-central Colorado the terrestrial beds overlying 1110 late Montanan marine deposits have been separated rather arbitrarily into two formatioris, the Vermejo and the overlying Raton. No vertebrates are known from either of these formatioris, so their age determinations must be based primarily on the fossil plants and on the evidence from the underlying marine rocks. The latter are the Trinidad sandstone, whose fauna appears to be late Montanan, probably somewhat older than true Fox Hills.l The Vermejo flora, adequately described by Knowlton⁷ was referred by him to Montanan age.2 The present study agrees in part with such an age assignment, as is shown in the following analysis of the V ermejo species:
